# gen119 (rung 19 + rung 13, deeper): goal-directed SEARCH — the planner agent.
# gen116 iterated ONE given action; gen118 INDUCED a rule from data; gen119 is the
# deductive complement: given a start, a target, and a SET of available actions,
# the agent SEARCHES the action space (breadth-first) and synthesizes the
# SHORTEST sequence of tool calls reaching the goal — means-ends problem solving.
# The plan is found each time (held-out transfer) and verified by replaying it
# (the trajectory shown is the real one); failure is admitted honestly.

# Synthesize the shortest plan from 3 to 28 with {x3, +1}: x3, x3, +1.
> from 3, using times 3 and add 1, reach 28.
< Reached 28 from 3 in 3 steps: 3 -[*3]-> 9 -[*3]-> 27 -[+1]-> 28.

# The proof trace is the real synthesized plan, not a stored answer.
> how do you know?
< Because search plan (3 steps): 3 -[*3]-> 9 -[*3]-> 27 -[+1]-> 28.

# A different goal and action set: 5 to 7 with {x2, -3} in two steps.
> from 5, using times 2 and subtract 3, reach 7.
< Reached 7 from 5 in 2 steps: 5 -[*2]-> 10 -[-3]-> 7.

# Held-out, longer plan: 1 to 20 with {+2, x2}.
> from 1, using add 2 and times 2, reach 20.
< Reached 20 from 1 in 4 steps: 1 -[+2]-> 3 -[+2]-> 5 -[*2]-> 10 -[*2]-> 20.

# Anti-impostor: with only doubling from an even start, an odd target is
# unreachable — the search exhausts and admits it instead of fabricating a plan.
> from 2, using times 2, reach 7.
< I couldn't reach 7 from 2 with those operations.
